fp|t-title|n#|5|at|Imagining the UNSEEN|fp||
n#|7|at|^^Saying that you need to ^*i imagine ^*n where the  UNSEEN  cards are is one thing, but learning  HOW  to do it is another.|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


n#|7|at|^^The single most important way to develop this skill, is to TRY.  Think back to the example.  When dummy was first visible, did you think of the  UNSEEN  spades.  Did you actually bother to think them out as a list of cards ?   If your answer to me is NO @- then start doing it.|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


n#|7|at|^^Of course COUNTING helps and ^*b aaBridge ^*n is full of ways to learn to count.  See on the Welcome page
^^^c {^*b Learn the Suit Distributions } ^*n (with video)    and   { ^*b How to - Defend like an Expert ^*n }
^^both of which have counting at their core.  The |cp|red|at|^*b Exam ^*n|cp||at| mode of ^*b Learn the Suit Distributions ^*n should be tried.^^^^^^|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


fp|t-title|at|Recognising the Positions|fp||
n#|7|at|^^In a way this is harder.  I know of no work that categorises Throw-ins as you would in every book on squeezes.  So this work will proceed by presenting ad hoc examples, generally trying to point out what you could / should have been looking for.    You can make your own collection and / or send any examples to me for inclusion here.^^^^^^| 
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


fp|t-title|at|Avoiding a Throw-in|fp||
n#|7|at|^^As you come to understand the subject, be on the lookout for being nailed  BY  a throw-in.  Say you have an ^*b AQ ^*n tenace, try not to be caught having to lead away from it to declarers King.  So try to keep an exit card if you can.| 
